      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "11153d2c3d13c027",
        "text": "Following guidelines formulated by [[Fritz Heider]] for the field of perceptual media (i.e. for operatively closed mental systems), we want to base the concept of medium (as distinct from form) on the distinction between loosely coupled and strictly coupled elements. The loose, soft, malleable structure of media gives forms a chance to imprint themselves, to assert themselves. At the same time, the medium remains. It appears at the form as also differently possible coupling, as contingency. Only the form can be observed directly, the medium has to be discovered – just as one can see from the footprints in the soil that feet hold together more firmly than soil. If one wants to observe the medium on his part, one must observe it as form and presuppose a further medium formed by it. The last, finally not observable medium would then be the matter (in the sense of the old European tradition) or, as we might say today, the world."
      },
      "after": "928b59dab0d9120a",
      "date": 1675679573128
